			<abstract>
				<p>Magnocellular and parvocellular pathways have been described as parallel, originating at the first synapse in the retina. The midget pathway has been depicted as a “private” transmission line from individual cones to the brain, where the retinal image is processed. Indeed, in the primate retina, there are two midget bipolar cells devoted to each cone (Masri et al. 2020 J Neurosci 40:8132), providing two full-resolution representations of the visual image at the bipolar cell terminals. As the major carrier of signals from cones to the inner plexiform layer (IPL), the midget bipolars are positioned to transmit and receive signals from numerous neuron types. Serial block-face scanning electron microscopy (EM) was used to reconstruct ON midget bipolar cells. Outgoing ribbon synapses and incoming conventional synapses were identified using classical EM criteria. Strikingly, each bipolar cell terminal was associated with over 100 postsynaptic interactions. Contrary to the 1:1:1 pathway from cone to midget ganglion cell, each midget bipolar cell made &gt;50 excitatory synapses onto cells other than the one midget ganglion cell it contacted, distributing signals to a dozen or more neurons. This included parasol cells, making midget bipolar signals divergent rather than parallel. Contrary to primarily functioning to transmit signals straight through to the brain, the IPL circuity is well-positioned to do much of the visual image processing before the signals arrive at the cortex.</p>
